Architecture plan for `mtplayground/process-bar-2`

Goal
Build a self-hosted blog/CMS on Next.js App Router with a protected admin area, PostgreSQL via Prisma, Credentials-based auth for a single admin flow, and public post rendering with SEO/feed support.

Module structure
- `app/`
  - `(public)/page.tsx` for the paginated home page
  - `(public)/posts/[slug]/page.tsx` for post detail
  - `admin/sign-in/page.tsx` for auth entry
  - `admin/posts/page.tsx` for dashboard
  - `admin/posts/new/page.tsx` for create flow
  - `admin/posts/[id]/edit/page.tsx` for edit flow
  - `layout.tsx`, `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, `not-found.tsx`
  - `sitemap.ts`, `robots.ts`, optional `rss.xml/route.ts`
- `components/`
  - `site/` header, footer, pagination, post cards
  - `admin/` dashboard table, post form, markdown editor, preview
  - `ui/` buttons, inputs, alerts, empty/error states
- `lib/`
  - `env.ts` for validated environment access
  - `db.ts` Prisma client singleton
  - `auth.ts` NextAuth config/helpers
  - `markdown.ts` render and excerpt helpers
  - `posts.ts` read-side post queries
  - `metadata.ts` shared SEO/Open Graph builders
  - `utils.ts` generic utilities
- `actions/`
  - `posts.ts` server actions for create/update/delete/publish
- `prisma/`
  - `schema.prisma`, `migrations/`, `seed.ts`
- `types/`
  - `post.ts` and `auth.ts` for app-level view models when Prisma types should not leak into UI
- `middleware.ts`
- root config
  - `next.config.*`, `tailwind.config.*`, `postcss.config.*`, `tsconfig.json`
  - `Dockerfile`, `docker-compose.yml`, `.env.example`

Shared types and data shape
- Prisma `User` model: `id`, `email`, `passwordHash`, `role`, `createdAt`, `updatedAt`
- Prisma `Post` model: `id`, `title`, `slug`, `excerpt`, `content`, `published`, `publishedAt`, `createdAt`, `updatedAt`, `authorId`
- App view types
  - `PostListItem` for home/admin tables
  - `PostDetail` for full render page
  - `PostFormInput` for create/edit validation
- Keep database entities in Prisma and expose UI-safe shapes from `lib/posts.ts` and server actions instead of importing raw Prisma types into many components.

Issue dependency order
- Foundation: #1 Next.js -> #2 Tailwind -> #3 env -> #4 Docker
- Data layer: #5 Prisma -> #6 models/migration -> #7 seed
- Auth layer: #8 NextAuth -> #9 sign-in -> #10 middleware
- Admin core: #11 post server actions -> #12 dashboard -> #13 markdown editor -> #14 create page -> #15 edit page
- Public site: #16 layout -> #17 home page -> #18 post detail -> #19 metadata -> #20 sitemap/robots -> #21 RSS
- Polish: #22 loading/error UI -> #23 validation/errors -> #24 README/deploy notes

Cross-cutting dependencies
- #3 env should define all keys needed by #4, #5, #8, #24 early to avoid churn.
- #6 should include `slug` and publish fields so #11, #17, #18, #19, #21 do not need schema changes later.
- #8 should settle session strategy and route helpers before #10, #11, #12, #14, #15.
- #13 should produce a reusable `PostForm` used by both #14 and #15 to avoid divergent editor behavior.
- #23 validation should wrap #11 actions and feed errors into #9, #14, and #15 rather than being handled separately in each page.

Key design decisions
- Use App Router server components for read-heavy pages and server actions for admin mutations. This keeps the stack simple and avoids adding a separate API layer for CRUD.
- Use Credentials auth with hashed passwords and a seeded admin user. Keep scope intentionally narrow; no public sign-up.
- Prefer `slug` as the public identifier and numeric/string `id` for admin editing routes.
- Store Markdown source in the database and render to HTML on the server for public pages; keep preview rendering client-side in the editor.
- Implement env validation once in `lib/env.ts` using a small schema validator so bad configuration fails fast in development and deployment.
- Centralize Prisma and NextAuth configuration to avoid duplicate initialization in server actions, route handlers, and middleware-adjacent helpers.
- Generate metadata, sitemap, and RSS from the same published-post query helpers so SEO outputs cannot drift from the rendered site.
- Aim for single-admin, low-complexity deployment assumptions in Docker Compose: Next.js app + PostgreSQL service, with documented env vars and migration/seed steps.

Risks to manage in later issues
- NextAuth version choice must match App Router patterns used by the selected Next.js version.
- Middleware should protect only `/admin` content pages and avoid redirect loops on `/admin/sign-in`.
- Markdown rendering must be sanitized if raw HTML is allowed; decide that policy before #18.
- Pagination, RSS, sitemap, and metadata should only include published posts.
- Docker and local development should share the same env contract to avoid split-brain configuration.
